description:
GOAL: Inter-process messaging. send(pid, msg) and receive primitives.
v1 is COPY-ONLY (the zero-copy fast path comes in .19.5).

## Prerequisites

- fz-ul4.19.1 — Runtime with worker pool + scheduler + Process registry.
- fz-ul4.19.2 — Pid surface (struct schema), spawn/self builtins.
- fz-ul4.19.6 — Atom-table policy (global, mutex-protected).
- fz-ul4.11.31 — HeapVisitor trait + walk_heap fn introduced. This
  ticket adds CopyVisitor as a new implementation.

## Decisions captured

- Each process owns a Vec<FzValue> mailbox (FIFO).
- send(pid, msg) deep-copies msg into receiver's heap (walks the
  FzValue closure-of-reachability and reallocates in receiver's heap),
  then enqueues into receiver's mailbox.
- receive blocks the current process until a message arrives. v1:
  receive returns the next message (no pattern selectivity; user
  matches at fz level).
- When send delivers to a Blocked process, scheduler marks it Ready
  and re-enqueues.
- Selective receive with pattern matching is a follow-up.
- Receive with timeout is a follow-up.
- Atom values inside messages: shared global ids per .19.6; no
  translation needed in deep-copy.

## Deliverables

### Mailbox (new src/runtime/mailbox.rs or fold into runtime/process.rs)

```rust
// On Process:
pub mailbox: VecDeque<FzValue>,
```

Push back from send; pop front from receive. v1: under pool size 1,
no cross-worker access; pool size N>1 would need a Mutex. Document.

### CopyVisitor (consumes .11.31's HeapVisitor)

```rust
pub struct CopyVisitor<'a> {
    src_heap: &'a Heap,
    dst_heap: &'a mut Heap,
    forwarding: HashMap<*mut HeapHeader, *mut HeapHeader>,
}

impl HeapVisitor for CopyVisitor<'_> {
    fn visit(&mut self, p: *mut HeapHeader, kind: HeapKind) -> WalkDecision {
        if let Some(&dst) = self.forwarding.get(&p) {
            return WalkDecision::Skip;   // already copied; shared substructure
        }
        let dst = alloc_in(dst_heap, kind, size_of(p));
        self.forwarding.insert(p, dst);
        // copy raw bytes; recursive visit will rewrite FzValue fields
        WalkDecision::Recurse
    }
}
```

Forwarding-pointer technique preserves sharing and terminates on
cycles (if any structural cycles ever existed — currently fz has no
mutation so they don't, but visitor must not assume).

Handles all HeapKinds: Struct, List, Bitstring, VecI64/F64/U8/Bit,
Map, Closure, Float.

### Builtins (fz_send / fz_receive)

```rust
extern "C" fn fz_send(receiver_pid_bits: u64, msg_bits: u64) -> u64 {
    let cur = current_process();
    let receiver_pid = decode_pid(receiver_pid_bits);
    runtime().with_task(receiver_pid, |receiver| {
        let mut copier = CopyVisitor::new(&cur.heap, &mut receiver.heap);
        walk_heap(FzValue(msg_bits), &cur.heap.schemas, &mut copier);
        let copied = FzValue(copier.forwarding[&unbox(msg_bits)] as u64);
        receiver.mailbox.push_back(copied);
        if receiver.state == State::Blocked {
            receiver.state = State::Ready;
            runtime().enqueue(receiver_pid);
        }
    });
    /* return :ok */
}

extern "C" fn fz_receive() -> u64 {
    let cur = current_process();
    if let Some(msg) = cur.mailbox.pop_front() {
        return msg.0;
    }
    cur.state = State::Blocked;
    /* trampoline-yield sentinel */
}
```

Wire as IR builtins or special prims; design at impl time.

### Scheduler integration

- send delivering to Blocked receiver: receiver state -> Ready;
  re-enqueue in run_queue.
- receive on empty mailbox: caller state -> Blocked; trampoline
  returns sentinel; worker yields.

## Tests

- Spawn process B; A sends [1, 2, 3] to B; B receives and prints.
  Both processes' heaps grew by the list size (independent copies).
- Send a tuple of mixed values.
- Send a deeply nested structure (list of maps of bitstrings).
- Send a value with sharing (tuple containing the same list twice):
  forwarding-ptr preserves sharing in destination.
- Mailbox FIFO ordering preserved.
- Receive blocks correctly (state becomes Blocked); send wakes it.
- Atom-identity preserved across send (per .19.6).

## Risks

- Deep-copy correctness across all HeapKinds. Mitigation: one test per
  kind. The HeapVisitor refactor in .11.31 centralizes the traversal.
- Sharing collapse: naïve recursive copy duplicates shared
  substructures. Mitigation: forwarding-ptr technique.
- Performance: deep copy is the v1 cost; .19.5 fixes hot cases.

## Out of scope

- Selective receive (follow-up).
- Receive timeout (follow-up).
- Zero-copy send fast path (.19.5).
- Static uniqueness for fast path (.19.7).
